Use the tidyr::uncount() function to expand a frequency variable, in this case lobster count

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>% 
  uncount(lobster_count)

Now each lobster has its own row. This is tidy format.

Now lets look at this data a bunch of ways.

For the histogram, use facet_wrap ~site to make different graphs for each site. Use scales = “free” to make the scales to scale for each graph

ggplot(lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +

              width = 0.2,
              alpha = 0.3)

Now we are going to use the ‘lubridate’ package to parse dates and times (we are going to make it date class) Use the explicit version of this package because it may show up in other packages

First I’m going to add a new column with ‘mutate()’, that contains my date as an actual date mdy is because the date is currently written as month/day/year. The lubridate function automatically puts the date into standard ISO format (YYYY-MM-DD)

lobster_date <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  mutate(
    date_new = lubridate::mdy(date)
  )

What if I want to sort by month

Now we will Parse ‘Date’ column to get the different pieces (month, year) separated. If object is in ‘date’ class, use lubridate::month function and it will pull the month. Use label = TRUE to change it to month name

lobster_parse_date <- lobster_date %>% 
  mutate(
    obs_month = lubridate::month(date_new, label = TRUE),
    obs_year = lubridate::year(date_new)
  )

Now we are going to count lobsters by different groupings using ‘count’ function Let’s say I want to count the number of lobsters by year and month

The ‘count’ function does a ‘group_by’ then ‘summarize’, then find the length, then lastly it ungroups the data

‘count’ is combination of ‘group_by’ and ‘tally’

lobster_ym <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  count(obs_year, obs_month) 

lobster_ysite <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  count(site, obs_year)

  
#Now...
# group by + summarize + n() to create a new table with mean size, and standard deviation function and sample size (n)

lobster_summary <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  group_by(site) %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_size = mean(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    sd_size = sd(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE),
    sample_n = n()
  )

Next we’ll do some confidence intervels and t-tests

Use the ‘t.test()’ function to find confidence intervals and perform t-tests

I wanna find confidence intervals for lobster sizes at isla vista use ‘pull()’ function to pull out the size_mm column into just one vector. Calling an indivudal column with using dataframe$columnname will do the same thing as vector

ivee_lobsters <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "IVEE") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

t.test(ivee_lobsters) # 95% confidence interval that in 95 percent in other samples I theoretically take IO would expdct teh sample mean to fall within this range. 
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  ivee_lobsters
## t = 245.23, df = 2302, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  72.99130 74.16806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  73.57968

default in onesample t test asking ifwe have enough evidence to think that actual value significnatly different than zero

Now…. Two sample t-test: Is there a significant difference in mean lobster lengths between Naples Reef and Mohawk Reef?

# method one (more tedious)

# pull the vectors

napl_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "NAPL") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "MOHK") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

# Now t test
mohk_napl_ttest <- t.test(napl_sample, mohk_sample)

mohk_napl_ttest
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  napl_sample and mohk_sample
## t = 19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  10.19806 12.43436
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  78.18454  66.86833

p value means that there is only a 2.2 x 10 to the minus 16th probability that i could have taken 2 samples from poulations with the same mean and found by random chance, means of my groups that are at least that different

p value is thep robability. So in our test, the probability is super low so we are going to assume thatwe took samples from populations that actually havedifferent means

inline referencing:

Mean lobster size differed significantly between Mohawk and Naples reef (t(1850.7720862) = 19.849)

Maybe an easier way to do a 2 sample t.test t.test function only works with 2 groups, so we need to make the dataframe 2 groups before doing the t test

# METHOD 2

#create data frame that only has 2 groups I want to compare

lobster_2sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site %in% c("NAPL", "MOHK"))

ttest_2 <- t.test(size_mm ~ site, data = lobster_2sample)

ttest_2
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  size_mm by site
## t = -19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -12.43436 -10.19806
## sample estimates:
## mean in group MOHK mean in group NAPL 
##           66.86833           78.18454
